  <h1>Common Civil Rights Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can sue the police department directly.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>You can sue the municipality that operates the department, but only under the <em>Monell</em> doctrine &mdash; you must show the violation resulted from an official policy, widespread custom, or deliberate indifference in training. Suing the department alone (without a Monell theory) will likely fail.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Qualified immunity means officers can never be sued.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Not quite. Qualified immunity shields officers when the right they violated was not &ldquo;clearly established.&rdquo; When there is analogous prior precedent &mdash; a case with similar enough facts showing the same conduct was unconstitutional &mdash; qualified immunity can be overcome. Some states have abolished or limited it for state-court claims.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Section 1983 covers federal government actors.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>False. Section 1983 only covers state and local government actors. Claims against federal officers are governed by <em>Bivens</em> doctrine, which has been substantially narrowed and is generally limited to a few specific contexts.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;If I wasn&rsquo;t physically harmed, I have no claim.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Not true. Nominal damages of $1 are available when a constitutional right was violated even with no actual harm proven (<em>Carey v. Piphus</em>, 1978). More importantly, attorney fees under &sect; 1988 are recoverable by a prevailing plaintiff even when only nominal damages are awarded in some circuits.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can get punitive damages against the city.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>No. <em>City of Newport v. Fact Concerts</em> (1981) bars punitive damages against municipalities. Punitive damages are available only against individual officers who acted with malice or reckless indifference to constitutional rights.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I need to go to an administrative agency first.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Generally not. Unlike Title VII or ADEA, &sect; 1983 requires no administrative exhaustion before filing in federal court. However, state notice-of-claim statutes (often with 90&ndash;180 day deadlines) must be satisfied before suing municipal defendants in many states.</p>
